text: On the Indian part of the video, it only featured the Yamuna river. What about the Ganges where even human corpses are being thrown? Their sizes may seem small, but they're actually difficult to clean due to the deposited trash over the years. But with zealous cooperation, it can be done. Imagine therefore the efforts needed with large bodies of water such as a river or a bay. Discipline, we seriously need more of this in my home-country. reply.author: Spencer Wilton
reply.text: The difference is in the culture. Japan's rivers were heavily polluted in the past by industrial effluent and sewage, but the population have never used the rivers as a means of disposing of rubbish. The individuals in Japan have always been very respectful of the environment, even if it was not within their power to change the sewage system and industry. In India everyone is only concerned for themselves, they dump their trash wherever is convenient for them- the streets, forests, rivers etc. Even if India cleaned up the sewage system and industry, the place would still be treated as a dump by the people. There is such a huge cultural difference between India and Japan that means it will take centuries before the population understands their behaviour is the problem.

reply.author: James Merryman
reply.text: Gihan Nadeera  That was a black Carp (Karasu goi in Japanese, or Crow Carp translated to English) that looks dark blue because of the (Vietnamese) cinematographer's heavy use of blue filtering. \n\nThere are actually 2 varieties of Koi with blue coloring: Asagi, which have a blue Matsuba (pinecone) pattern on their back with red or orange red coloring on their sides, and Shushui, which have the same coloring, but don't have the Matsuba pattern because they have Doitsu (German, as derived from German "Mirror Carp") scales. The blue is more of a bright slate blue than the true blue you see in Blue Damselfishes or Blue Discusfishes, but it is still very pretty. There are videos showing both varieties of Koi on YouTube.

reply.author: James Merryman
reply.text:
Nor Priest According to the World Health Organization's most current  tabulated data (for 2017), Japan is in 26th place by suicide rates relative to population size. While these figures represent reported suicides, I would certainly consider them more reliable than internet comment board hearsay. The countries clustered at the top are very poor or mostly very poor nations where a large percentage of the population has become hopelessly trapped in poverty and in many cases, ever worsening debt. The exceptions are mostly former Soviet bloc nations struggling with a declining standard of living.

Sri Lanka is currently at the top of the list, with 34.6 suicides per 100,000 citizens. India is 24th, AHEAD of 26th place Japan, with 16 suicides per 100,000 citizens. As you know, desperately poor Indian farmers trapped in ever worsening debt account for a large % of India's suicides, and Sri Lanka's high suicide rate reflects the upheavals and ethnic and religious divisions behind their recent longstanding civil war.

People who post the usual painfully ill informed cliches about Japanese suicide rates should note that Japan's suicide rate has remained relatively stable, while those of many other countries have skyrocketed within recent years. These include New Zealand (which now has one of the highest adolescent suicide rates in the world), and my own country, the US. 

Shintoism and Buddhism do not maintain the absolute condemnation of suicide as a damnable sin that is a tenant of Christianity. They also foster a belief in reincarnation (and with it, the possibility of greater honor/success/redemption in a new life), while Christianity opposes belief in reincarnation. (You well know that Hinduism condemns suicide as a form of murder.) Surprising, then, that so many of the countries at the top of the list are predominately Christian nations.

Singapore gives Japan some serious competition for cleanliness, even though it is much more densely populated overall relative to land mass. 

Japan's cities are densely populated, but the extensive mountainous areas are sparsely populated, with most of their human inhabitants concentrated in villages and towns. 

Japan's remarkable tradition of cleanliness dates back many centuries, and is largely a cultural and practical adaptation to life in very crowded towns and cities prior to the Meiji era. Singapore's largely government encouraged and imposed cleanliness is much more recent; a post colonial development. 

And before someone reiterates the usual tiresome and ignorant "I wanna feel good about myself by trashing others" cliches, Japan is currently 26th in the World Heath Organization's list of nations by suicide rates by population, and does not currently cope with high radiation levels, and Singapore does not cane people for littering or chewing gum!

reply.author: James Merryman
reply.text:
Comma Kazi You completely missed the point of my post, which was that nations can achieve both a high standard of cleanliness AND a culture of cleanliness in many different ways. Note that a culture of cleanliness is essential for a nation to become and stay clean; government 'control' alone cannot accomplish this.

I've visited Singapore 7 times (my favorite country to visit after Japan, but this Westerner does find their year round heat and humidity increasingly difficult to deal with because of my age). Singapore is a VERY DENSELY POPULATED tiny island; that demographic makes cleanliness much more difficult to maintain, but they have succeeded at this very well. Singapore was NOT very clean or orderly when I first visited in 1959 (when it was still a British colony). 

You well know that many tiny islands that are far less densely populated than Singapore are very polluted and/or littered with trash.

One important point that I omitted earlier; Singapore has a Tamil population that represents over 7% of their citizens, but their residences and businesses, in Singapore's "Little India", and elsewhere, are as clean and tidy as the rest of Singapore (which also means that they make any city here in the US look dirty by comparison).

Also agree that things are slowly improving, and that mainland China is generally much cleaner than India, but generally much dirtier than Japan and Singapore, as well as Hong Kong, Taiwan, and Macau. Spitting and littering were also commonplace in Singapore during the late 1950s, the situation is now VERY different. I NEVER observed littering or spitting in Japan, even during my first visit in 1957.

Shanghai's relative cleanliness is more complex than a matter of face; it is, and has long been, China's most cosmopolitan city, so standards and mores of behavior are more amenable to outside perspectives and influences, relative to say, Beijing.
